{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:31:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:31:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16309"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16309"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9000"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58865"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1099"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7482"},{"type":"tags","id":"8399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21425"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe middle ear normally contains a simple columnar epithelium. However, certain conditions can lead to the presence of abnormal tissue types within this space.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a cholesteatoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benign skin growth in abnormal location that can expand and destroy nearby structures","Inflammatory mass composed of granulation tissue","Benign bony growth arising from the temporal bone","Collection of cholesterol crystals within the middle ear","Malignant tumour of the middle ear epithelium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echolesteatoma is a benign skin growth in an abnormal location that can expand and destroy nearby structures\u003C/strong\u003E. It consists of keratinising squamous epithelium that forms a sac-like structure filled with accumulated keratin debris. While benign, its expansile nature can cause significant local destruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Einflammatory mass composed of granulation tissue\u003C/strong\u003E better describes the changes seen in chronic otitis media without cholesteatoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenign bony growth arising from the temporal bone\u003C/strong\u003E describes an osteoma, which typically occurs in the external auditory canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecollection of cholesterol crystals within the middle ear\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in chronic otitis media and can be found incidentally during surgical treatment of a cholesteatoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignant tumour of the middle ear epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E would be a different pathological process entirely, such as squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECholesteatomas can cause complications including hearing loss, facial nerve paralysis, and intracranial infection due to their destructive nature and tendency to become infected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A cholesteatoma is an abnormal growth of keratinising squamous epithelium in the middle ear that can cause progressive bone destruction.","Cholesteatomas can be congenital or acquired, with acquired being more common due to chronic middle ear dysfunction.","The expanding mass of keratin debris can erode surrounding structures including the ossicles, facial nerve, and inner ear."],"references":["Pachpande TG, Singh CV. Diagnosis and Treatment Modalities of Cholesteatomas: A Review. Cureus. 2022 Nov 6;14(11):e31153. doi: 10.7759/cureus.31153. PMID: 36505121; PMCID: PMC9731553.","Chang P, Kim S. Cholesteatoma--diagnosing the unsafe ear. Aust Fam Physician. 2008 Aug;37(8):631-8. PMID: 18704212.","Kennedy KL, Singh AK. Middle Ear Cholesteatoma. 2024 Aug 9. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846338."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58865"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16309"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58865"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T15:54:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T09:48:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9000"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73399"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"head